				 <!-- D/JQA/50 January 1847 P 967 -->
				
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-01-01">
					<head>1 January 1847</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-01-01"/><editor
						role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Recreation</subject></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
				<p>on Friday the <date>1<hi rend="superscript">st.</hi> of January 1847.</date> I rode out in a carriage
					with <persRef ref="adams-charles2">my Son’s</persRef> wife <persRef ref="adams-abigail4">Abby B. Adams</persRef> and I rode out with her from an hour to an hour
					and a half every day till Friday 22 Jan<hi rend="superscript">y</hi> when I took a short
					walk in the Street—</p>
					</div>
				</div>
				<div type="entry" xml:id="jqadiaries-v50-1847-01-18">
					<head>18 January 1847</head>
					<bibl><author>JQA</author><date type="creation" when="1847-01-18"/><editor
						role="transcription">Neal Millikan</editor>
					<subject>Adams Family Relations</subject>
					<subject>Adams Family Finances</subject></bibl>
					<div type="docbody">
				<p>On the <date>18<hi rend="superscript">th.</hi> of January 1847.</date> I executed my last will and
					Testament, which I had been several weeks preparing and dictating to <persRef ref="adams-charles2">my son</persRef>— The
					witnesses were <persRef ref="brooks-edward">Edward Brooks</persRef>, <persRef ref="foster-james">James H. Foster</persRef> and <persRef ref="spooner-allen">A. C. Spooner</persRef> who made the
					final draft of the will— I keep a copy of the will in my possession and deliver
					the will itself to my Son Charles Francis Adams, my sole Executor and Residuary
					legatee.</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
